Title: Correspondence using Mahalanobis Distance, Dynamic Programming, and Relaxation.  
Author: Nicolas Merlet 
Address: 91904 Jerusalem, Israel  
Affiliation: Institute of Computer Science The Hebrew University of Jerusalem  
Abstract: We present a new solution to the correspondence problem. It is based on dynamic programming, and can deal with image sequences. The overall potential characterizes the quality of matching of a point, and dynamic programming achieves consistency independently for each edge of the new image. The overall potential is defined on a pair of points as a function of two components : a potential defined for each new point as a function of its Mahalanobis distance to the old edges, and a potential associated to their respective edges on the basis of their relative distance and orientation. Finally, occlusions, artifacts and ambiguities are dealt with by applying relaxation to the different solutions found by dynamic programming, where the compatibility coefficients associated to the empty label are updated at each iteration.
