Reference-contexts: Dynamic programming is a successful method of optimization. The basic approach consists in defining a cost or potential depending on the local characteristics of the image and to perform an iterative summation-minimization process. The absence of any threshold is an important factor of robustness. In particular, Baker <ref> [1] </ref> and Ohta [5] showed how to apply it to the correspondence problem. They first rectify the pair of stereo images so that the epipolar lines are parallel to the scan-lines. <p> A 2D array is then built for a couple of corresponding lines, and the cost measures the similarity between corresponding features, grey-levels, and intervals. The consistency between successive lines is achieved either with a cooperative process to correct errors <ref> [1] </ref> or by searching a 3D space [5]. In our solution, the overall potential characterizes the quality of matching of a point and its sum is computed along each edge. This potential has two components.
